column1: #Text=Egyptian prime minister steps down ; armed forces appoint former transport minister to position
#Text=Ahmed Shafik , Egypt 's acting prime minister , has resigned , the Supreme Council of the Armed Forces , now in control of the country , announced yesterday .

#Text=Shafik was appointed to his position by then Egyptian president Hosni Mubarak during the 2011 Egypt anti-government protests , not long before Mubarak decided to resign as president on February 11 , 2011 .
#Text=Meanwhile , a number of his cabinet ministers have retained their positions .
#Text=Shafik had received criticism for his negative attitude towards young protesters and his " inadequate vision " , according to the Los Angeles Times .

#Text= The Supreme Council of the Armed Forces decided to accept the resignation of Prime Minister Ahmed Shafiq and appointed Essam Sharaf to form the new government , " the armed forces said on social networking website Facebook .

column1: #Text=Sharaf formerly held the position as the Minister of Transportation .

#Text=The Los Angeles Times reports that he departed from that position five years ago , during the aftermath of numerous train collisions in which the Egyptian government was accused of carelessness .
#Text=Former Egyptian president Hosni Mubarak was considered persona non grata by Egypt on Monday , as was his family .
#Text=According to BBC News Online , Mubarak is not in the good health and has yet been seen or heard from in public since his resignation .
#Text=Despite having achieved one of their aims , protesters intend to continue demonstrating with mass rallies on Friday because all their demands have yet to be met .
#Text=The removal of a current emergency law is amongst those demands .
#Text=The law allows the Egyptian government to place people under arrest without charges brought against them .
#Text=In a statement , the January 25 Youth Coalition said that they " still demand a specific time frame to achieve the rest of the revolution 's basic demands .
